MY INTEREST
“What are they?” How would you answer that? Female? Human? (other word)? It seems like a pretty (broad/question) question that you
wouldn’t begin to know how to answer, but growing up, this is was a very clear question. a question my family asked each other a lot. What we
this was the shorthand (abbreviated) way of asking “What’s their personality type?”
This all started with
I’ve had a fascination with personality for most of my life
My mom started learning about Myers Briggs when I was 5 years old and a lot of that knowledge was passed onto to me as it was something that
became an important part of all of our lives
It is something that I still use today and have gotten into the habit of trying to “type” people when I first meet them, or at least after getting a good
sense of what they’re like and what their thought process might be.
Not only do I just find it interesting and fun, but it helps me to understand why people do or say the things they do, and why a lot of things that we
might assume about people isn’t true, it’s just a different way of observing the world and then different way of processing what we observe.
Why some people seem cold but don’t understand why. Why some people are brutally honest (list a few)
(what makes people tick, what bothers people, what hurts people’s feelings. When something doesn’t affect you the same way, it can sometime
confuse you. What’s wrong with this person? They need to calm down. It’s not that big of a deal)
(why can’t this person do or understand this thing that’s so easy for me? They must not be very smart)
(why one person may want to go to go out and why another might want to stay home.
While some of these traits may appeal to some people and not appeal to others (ie, why we all like different kinds of people), there is not a single
bad personality trait and not one that’s better than the other. Not a single personality trait that needs to be fixed or changed. Not one. (talk about
behavior/character vs personality?).
NO BAD PERSONALITIES - BUT PEOPLE THINK THERE ARE
We may on the surface recognize and agree that we all have different personalities, but subconsciously we don’t look at them as their own dif
ferent personality, we look at them as deviating from our own personality. Often times when we see a person react to a situation differently than
we would, get upset about something we wouldn’t, not enjoy the things we do, or as easily understand the things that we do, we interpret it as a
fault, not a difference. They must be missing something.
-not everyone is going to like every personality trait, why not everyone gets along, but they are all valid, none of them need to be “fixed”
•the harmful effects of misunderstanding personality
-People would understand that just because someone doesn’t do things the way they do it, have the skills they do, think the way they do,
doesn’t mean they’re wrong. This has been the bane of my existence.
BIG 5 EXAMPLE
The most celebrated personality type in the US would be Extroverted Intuitive Feeler Judger
Personality trait most known
What’s interesting is that although I test low for Feeling(whatever the name) and Judging, I am an INFJ. I have only one characteristic off, but that
difference changes how I use and display these other characteristics.
And that goes for any combination* (make footnote about exclusion of neuroticm). All of these traits, are celebrated if they belong to an extrovert.
If an introvert has these traits, they don’t display them in the same way. The Big 5 treats introverts as sad, empty shells (who would be happier if
only they were willing to work harder to reap those social rewards).

What big 5 is
How it judges personality (all characteristics are positive words)

If translating this into MBTI (ENJF), I’m only one characteristic off from their perfect personality (INFJ). So if you were to translate it back into Big

The one that gets to me most: lack of extroversion.
Bias towards extroverts (outgoing) – what is it perceived as
Job interviews
Talk to customers. I have avoided going to places because the people talk to me too much
The Big 5 simplifies personality to the point that it has no meaning. It looks at the first layer of a person, their perceived behavior that they show to
the world, as a way to define their personality. It does not by any means go into details of why a person might display this behavior and explain
why it’s often not for the reasons you think it is.
Openness to experience - imaginative, open-minded, experimental

Creative, imaginative, adventurous, intellectual, unconventional, artistically inclined
“High openness scorers are more likely to have a high IQ”
Conscientiousness - conscientious, disciplined, efficient, well organized
2nd “People who are low in conscientiousness are more likely to develop addictions of all kinds...”
Reserved, formal, serious, quiet - Extraversion (Se) - outgoing, friendly, assertive, likes working with others
2nd “Introverts tend to conserve their energy, and do not work as hard to earn these social rewards” “WORK AS HARD”???!??!?!??!?!! “People
who are low in extroversion do not experience the same “high” from these experiences, and so do not put in as much effort to pursue them.”
Agreeableness - compassionate, eager to please, good natured
2nd
“Low scorers tend to be hostile, competitive, and antagonistic”
Neuroticism
“A person’s tendency to experience negative emotions
Certain personalities tend to develop more anxiety than others, but it is because their personality does not work as well with the societal system
that we have created as it does for other personality types. It’s a similar reason why a person with autism is considered to be disabled, because
the way they think doesn’t correlate with how the general population thinks, their minds “don’t work right” because they don’t work like the majority,
thus they are disabled. Society’s system was developed by people, it is not a part of nature. Some personalities weren’t lucky enough to have it
cater to them. Being expected to think and behave in a way that is unnatural to them, leading to them doing it poorer than others, would under
standably cause some anxiety – Excuse me, Neuroticism.
EXTROVERSION (introversion/extroversion)
I make friends easily
I really enjoy large parties and gatherings

These are the misconceptions that the Big 5 has and spreads around. Most of the people you see in the world are strangers. Passersby. You
make a quick judgement about them from what you see in front of you. (If you believe that the person see in front of you is always an accurate
depiction of personality (rephrase), then the Big 5 would, more or less, be more accurate.) But that’s not how personality works. Personality isn’t
the behavior (that you project to the world) that most people see, it’s how you work in your head.
The big 5 could easily be (altered, skewed) due to mental illness. They actually include what’s basically an indicator of mental illness or distress
as one of the 5 criteria that makes up a person’s personality.
I don’t initiate conversations with people I don’t know. I don’t care for small talk with strangers and won’t put in the effort to keep the conversation
going. Just because I don’t speak doesn’t mean I don’t have a lot to say. What does not having a lot to say imply? If you don’t say what you’re
thinking that you must not be thinking anything?
There is a clear bias towards extroversion. Because it doesn’t even acknowledge introversion. An introvert, according to the Big 5, is someone
who lacks introversion. Neuroticism seems to have a lot of countering traits to extroversion. Introverts are just neurotic.
I got a 2 in extroversion. I’m going out on a limb, but that might be because I’m an introvert.
MYERS BRIGGS EXPLANATION OF BIG 5 ASSUMPTIONS
You are not on a scale of one (“personality’, cross out) trait (scale of extroversion, you do not lack intuition, you do not lack feeling, you do not lack
judging. You aren’t a deviant from one perfect personality. you are one of two different and equally (beneficial, good, w/e) personality traits that
make up your four-letter code.
NOW FOCUS ON INTROVERSION

stood

stood
• shy/outgoing (before awareness)
-Before these words started being spread around (started entering people’s vocabulary), they were referred to as “shy” and “outgoing”
-There was a clear and (unabashed? ) preference for “outgoing” personalities
-when describing a person, “she’s friendly, fun, happy, outgoing!” while shy is “well, he’s shy, but...” But what? (No shame.)
-Nonetheless, it was exciting to hear the words “introvert” and “extrovert” more and more. Finally, people would understand.
- heard the phrase “it’s where you get your energy” - I couldn’t believe it.
-When I heard the words, it was like hearing a language that only a few others spoke. I couldn’t help but always listen in.
-however, I quickly noticed there was something wrong with the way they spoke. Sentences were structured oddly, verbs weren’t conjugated
correctly, and there was a very, very strong accent.
-It’s clear nothing has changed. People know the words, but (never bothered to learn the language) don’t speak the language.
It’s not just about how quiet you are, it’s not even just about where you get your energy, it’s also about how you take in and process information,
and whether your other personality traits occur internally or externally
CAT/DOG
Are you a cat or a dog person?
Expecting an introvert to display happiness by going out talking loud and expressively with a large group of people is like expecting and cat to
show its happiness by running around a park barking and wagging its tail. You’re not going to see it.
cats/dogs comparison (cat people/dog people why is it that extroverts prefer dogs and introverts prefer cats. (as a stereotype))
Cats have resting bitch face. People naturally read their faces like they do human faces. Dogs have a welcoming face, either they have a big smile
or they give you sad puppy dog eyes.
A cat who goes off by itself, doesn’t want to be held, etc., doesn’t hate you. Trying to treat a cat like a dog angers it, it will distance itself from you
because it knows
Cats want peace. The first argument someone makes when they prefer dogs is always, always, always that “they greet you at the door” (and then
go on to list other traits that cats will also display if treated right. )
My theory is is that if someone owns/has owned a cat, and that’s their first argument, they’re mistreating their cat. Their cat is depressed.
My theory is that if you treat a cat right, it will greet you at the door, it will sit with you, it will look for you just so it can sleep next to you because it
just wants to be near you, it will love you. Because it knows that it’s ok to sit in silence around you. Treat it like a dog, it will distance itself from
you. And a cat that gets no interaction is depressed.
(RUDENESS)
If a cat does not (reciprocate) the (misguided) love and attention you try to give it, and instead of changing your own behavior to better suit the cat,
you (obtain) a universal view that all cats are angry and boring, who’s the one being (rude)?
If you smile and say hi to someone on the street and they don’t even look at you, they’re not angry, they don’t hate you, they’re not being rude.
They actually realize that they’re coming off as rude, and they don’t enjoy it, but even something as small as eye contact, a smile, and a wave
takes energy. And sometimes we just don’t have enough to spare. (I’ve crossed the street because I just don’t have the energy)
If you’re talking to someone and
Iii. in social interactions, what is rudeness?
When you smile and wave at someone on the street and they don’t even look at you, is that rude? If you’re standing in an elevator and try to
make conversation and they don’t (reciprocate), is that rude? If you’re sitting on the bus and try to talk to the person next to you and they pretend
they didn’t hear you, is that rude? Maybe. In some situations it could be, and you’d never really know. But is it always rude? Is it even rarely rude?
In my introverted opinion, no.
WHAT DOES INTROVERSION FEEL LIKE (why we are “rude”)
a. A battery analogy. A conversation with a stranger takes up energy that we don’t want to waste. When you’re out of energy, the ache to
get home is unbearable. And the relief to get to an empty how is unbeatable.
B. Our home base is in our head. (explain the Myers Briggs type science) All I’m saying is that there’s reasoning behind people’s differences.
DISCLAIMER
I don’t hate extroverts
My gripe isn’t with extroverts. I love extroverts. Some of best friends are extroverts. I held a door for an extrovert once. In all honesty, despite my
introversion activism, I do tend to gravitate to extroverts more than I do introverts. If I wanted to up my preachy level to an 11 I could explain exact
ly why, because there’s a reason.
I don’t mean to insult extroverts. I’m trying to bring them down to a middle ground to sit side by side with introverts. Silence doesn’t have to be un
comfortable. Silence doesn’t always need to be filled. A conversation to fill the silence can be just as uncomfortable for some people as it is for
others to sit in silence.
I prefer extroverts .. and go on..
it doesn’t mean that an extrovert should have to constantly cater to introverts. They deserve to be comfortable as well, and so it’s hard for both to
win. And you can’t always tell who’s an introvert. I don’t believe an extrovert is a terrible person for not walking on eggshells around an introvert.
All I ask is every now and then it you see a cat on the sidewalk, just let it be.
